$ SQL Server: table

A new table is created with the → development/databases/SQL-Server/sql/create/table[`create table`] statement and can be removed with
the → development/databases/SQL-Server/sql/drop/table[`drop table`] statement.

The → development/databases/SQL-Server/administration/schemas/sys/tables[`sys.tables`] view lists the tables and can be used to query for tables that meet certain characteristics such as their name, or which
→ development/databases/SQL-Server/administration/schemas[schema] they belong to.
-
Alternatively, the stored procedure → development/databases/SQL-Server/administration/schemas/sys/objects/stored-procedures/sp_tables[`sp_tables`] might be used.

In order to show column names of a given table or to search for columns with certain characteristics, the view → development/databases/SQL-Server/administration/schemas/sys/objects/views/columns[`sys.columns`] or stored procedure
→ development/databases/SQL-Server/administration/schemas/sys/objects/stored-procedures/sp_columns[`sp_columns`] might help.


sa:

  → development/databases/SQL-Server/T-SQL/data-types/table[`table`] is also a → development/databases/SQL-Server/T-SQL/data-types[T-SQL data type].

  → development/databases/SQL-Server/scripts/parent-and-child-tables_pl[`parent_and_child_tables.pl`] is a → development/languages/Perl script that shows a table's primary and foreign key.

  → development/databases/SQL-Server/T-SQL/user-defined-functions/table-valued
 
